In the Czech Republic, too, the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there, has been demonstrated.
Case of shares in Asia
A dramatic case occurred on Tuesday on the stock exchanges in Asia, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock exchange index lost nearly four percentage points over the business day, but later it was able to offset some of the losses, reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then lost to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan stock exchange fell by 3.6 percent according to the index there.
"The timing of the rescue action in the US is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide," said the Head of Monetary Authority in Hong Kong Joseph Yam.
Although it belongs to China, Hong Kong determines its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese Central Bank.
Hong Kong interest rates are moving at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt the draft financial support.
Otherwise, other countries would also be affected by the invasion.
A bloodbath of American shares
The American House of Representatives rejected on Monday the plan to support the financial system, for which up to $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion Kč) should be spent.
The legislators thus ignored President George Bush's request to support the plan.
Bush believes that the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help to stabilise the entire economy.
The American shares experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the most important stock indices recorded the largest break-in in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost seven percent, and a similar break-in he had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was hardly any sign that the draft would not pass through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concessions: US government is allowed to pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the American Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of an agreement on financial aid for the American financial system.
That is to be agreed at the beginning of next week.
The US legislators reached a breakthrough in talks about the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of financial aid for the American financial system totalling $700 billion (about 12 trillion).
However, this does not mean a victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated at the American Congress on Monday.
On Sunday this was said by Barney Frank, Chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee of the Reuters Agency.
According to various reports in the Senate, it is likely that the plan could be voted on at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a communication on the adoption of the plan should be the first major psychological factor for stimulating financial markets.
However, this is followed by a "disillusionment" due to the complex mechanisms, which could also help markets in practice.
Paulson: The Plan Must Be Effective
"We have achieved significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilise the market should look like," said Democratic Nancy Pelosi to the Bloomberg agency.
According to her words, there could still be a final vote on Sunday.
Legislators met with the American Finance Minister Henry Paulson the night of Sunday to give his final form to the government fund.
This provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which cause the financial companies to fall into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective on the market.
You have to continue with the healing plan, but I think we're on target," Paulson says.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets which are falling sharply.
According to the words of the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, the legislators were trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
This is to reassure investors of transactions in the Asian financial markets, which lie in the first time zone, where a Congress decision could affect the business on Monday.
But until now it is not quite clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is also uncertainty as to whether the negotiations could not fail at the last minute.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the next few days.
However, the law will still be subject to some changes.
The total amount earmarked for assistance to the scheme shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion will be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
However, the Congress can block the disbursement of the rest of the money if it has the impression that the program does not fulfil its function, for another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush values positive progress in negotiations
Although the President has a veto right in this decision, the Congress can vote in favour of his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea behind the programme has remained, based on the fact that hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages for buying bad mortgage securities.
"We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, the Senate then on Monday," says Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The American President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman Tony Fratto stated that Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "estimate the efforts of both sides to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy".
Restriction of golden umbrellas
The chairman of the Banking Committee of the Senator Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, stated that the legislators had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the conclusion of discounts and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law should also limit the so-called golden umbrellas for directors of companies involved in the programme and set up a committee to monitor the fund.
The Ministry of Finance shall be responsible for this task.
"We have worked very hard on this and achieved great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," says Paulson.
The plan also expects to help homeowners who have problems with the repayment of their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages that it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly cost to debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea according to the main economist of Patria Finance David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
"And that's because you don't know what mechanism and what price the problematic assets are bought up through.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government split the losses among themselves," said Marek this week to the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week, Marek believes that it is not decisive.
"It is much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and that they adopt it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on adoption is at this moment the most important," Marek stressed.
