The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be waiting any longer.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTū, which drew attention to the fact that the price of a text message here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps taken by the European Commission in regulating roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators are pleased to say that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTū) Pavel Dvo the Czech telecommunications authority, who in the past had often said that there was no room for another supplier in the Czech Republic.
It is true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (otherwise, it would probably not even find frequencies).
But there is one more possibility - a virtual provider.
In particular, the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a significant reduction in prices, which then also had to be addressed by traditional mobile operators.
Before the entry into the UK market, such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile still had similar votes as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has proved that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't need to look for examples for long.
In February this we reported on the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus to become the country's fifth largest provider.
At the back of Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon among others in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a traditional provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but this is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to put on a non-cliche target group.
This provider is specifically directed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept could be applied in the Czech Republic as in Poland.
The press speaker at Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubted this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile operators believe that
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly hopeful.
There will be a market entry of Mobilking in other countries in our region," says Jana Studničková, President of the Penta Financial Group, in a telephone call.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to do so.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
For a long time, their interest in starting a virtual mobile service provider has been showing the GTS Novera Group, which wants to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only landline, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we were already able to make progress in the negotiation process," said Pavel Kaidl, the press speaker.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a fully-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has great specificities vis-à-vis other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Srše the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificities of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Martina Kemrová’s press speaker rarely adds to the O2 statement: “Until now, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further.”
And she adds, "T-Mobile's network will hardly be a virtual provider by the end of the year.
At this moment, we already need a concrete offer to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure sharing.
This is precisely what we regard as the best from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area lies in the search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The mobile operators' approach is easy to understand, another provider was called more competition, which would lead to a fall in prices and therefore also a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the suppliers can pull a strand when it comes to something also proves the long way around the emergence of U:fon.
The strongest pressure towards ČTū was at the time when U:fon came on the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This also demonstrates the publicly available information from the ČTő websites.
Now U:fon is the reason why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile service provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and above all on its services."
However, in view of the approach taken by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of ČTū, which unfortunately, unlike Britain and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czechs.
It has only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem its very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider has been concluded through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not of sufficient interest to the classic providers," said Kristián Chapupo in his answer to our request from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a wording would not be surprising by the representatives of the providers.
This is more than worrying from an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, is supposed to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chapaus adds: "Where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a lowering of prices in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost already touching harmony of the three mobile operators is really shocking, resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just like the absolutely same petrol price at the petrol stations is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"In this case, the Authority has found no evidence to suggest that there is anti-competitive action, and thus it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant position on the market, so it does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its actions on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are likely to be lacking from the telecoms regulatory authority," said Chapau in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by the ČTū, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for a virtual provider to enter the market.
And the mobile service provider - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if this argument is not taken into account, it should at least be a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting similarly.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the company GTS Novera mentioned above) demonstrate that they face very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The reversal of responsibility for the ČTū is then a rather common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment of the Telecommunications Act has failed to bring about the expansion of ČTī's competences in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay if nobody looks at you.
First of all, the operation of some pseudovirtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
It is companies which issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Normally, these are companies that operate in the multi-level marketing sector.
Own mobile telephone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The joke is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar types of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be an infringement of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which can lead to the termination of cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that this will not be the case with the mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three mentioned companies it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, the activities of these companies do not lead them to neglected profits, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all that the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of the customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone does not run on its name, so they cannot fully possess it as the normal customers of mobile providers."
Even this alone, however, would have to happen at least strangely.
A further question also opens up for the ÚOHS.
Before such a procedure, mobile operators are blinding themselves to why they are blocking themselves against a virtual provider.
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to identify such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to satisfy itself with the statement of suppliers, they did not know anything about it and their business conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As the text has pointed out several times, the entry of virtual providers brought about a marked fall in prices for the various services.
Practically in all countries where virtual providers were created, traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies, which by no means sought to safeguard the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers, intervened at these very times.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are turning to the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get the impression that uncertainty in our competences is more than favorable in these cases.
But let us not throw the flute into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile market may soon be moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
