The Prague transport companies also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of Prague's transport companies as a date when the first passengers enter a subway, tram or bus, which carries an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the chip card Opencard.
The passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it played on their chip card at the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the U-Bahn stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádra the Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Let fory, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons have also been available on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until afternoon hours.
Those who use internet sales can really forget the output window at subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via internet, it is played on the open card in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, travellers can also have a switch with trained staff that advises interested parties about buying the Internet and also plays the coupon on the map," said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons on the open card at self-service machines, which are installed in some subway buses.
What do such automatic machines look like?
They are red, reminding of ticket drivers, the passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but it should be eighty until the end of the year," adds Opatrný.
The coupon controls an automaton instead of the driver
Operating the machines that will work from tomorrow is easy.
All you have to do is introduce the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays on its own.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburbs and on the bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants mainly come from the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia to the capital.
"In the trains that belong to the Prague integrated transport system, the train-accompanied readers have to check the validity of the coupons according to time and zone," says Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid. "This organisation compiles the timetables for the Prague transport operations.
The city buses have card readers at the check-in desk with the driver.
When entering, the chip card must not only be shown by the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked position at the side of the cash desk.
Thus the driver controls the validity of the played coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the played coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver to provide this information," Drápal said.
A passenger who does not ride by city buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon will end, in turn, can go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
