Among scientists, for years, a mysterious phenomenon has caused confusion - the swing-by-anomaly.
The Swing-by is a flight manoeuvre of space probes in which they receive additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
This allows the probes to save a lot of fuel.
The European-American research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick as well as the solar probe Ulysses.
However, what the researchers have been surprised by this for years: the missiles do not behave 100% as would be expected according to the old-fashioned gravity law.
Rather, there are irregularities in speed.
The probes are unexpectedly faster or slower.
So far, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They called him swing-by-anomaly.
Some experts fear that even Albert Einstein’s general theory of relativity, which describes the attraction of matter through a curvature of space, might not be entirely correct.
American physicist Stephen Adler from the Institute for Advanced Study from Princeton still firmly believes that Einstein was not wrong, and tries to explain the swing-by anomaly with the help of the so-called dark matter that astronomers have figured out in the universe.
"Responsible to the anomaly could be dark matter, which could also be very close to the Earth," he writes.
The space scientists have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
It is obviously a force of attraction whose effect can be observed on other heavenly bodies.
