Isabel Bayón calls back the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville worships a dancer who also comes from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalan (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother was Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in Triana, and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and an expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first women fighters for the emancipation of women, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, a vegetarian, and stood for the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
The life of this woman, who left her mark on the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the time between the wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
`I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested to me this role, which seemed impossible to me.'
"We are not trying to tell you about her life, save her spirit," said the flamenco dancer.
Her dance backgrounds helped me a lot in flamenco.
`The dancing of the butterfly' appeared to me like Guajira, for example, or `the dancing of the serpent' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area, she claims.
The production counts with two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing for Isabel in one of her ideas, as he did in `La puerta aberera'; and with flamenco master Matilde Coral, who wanted to work exceptionally with one of her ex-students.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I feel very honoured.'
The production also counts with musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the vocals of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he `takes over the role of the companion of the artists who were divas, in which he always falls in love.'
This work also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who became known in places as far away as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, although she has normally lived in London.
`I wanted to call her back, because I think she is one of the women who have a tremendous influence on a particular era and whose works today no one can appreciate anymore, and therefore even less', Bayón claims.
The show will take place today at 20:30 at the Theater Lope de Vega.
