Discussion - The blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of her founding yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it regained the confidence of the public, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross during the 1980s were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In the face of this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, the Government of Canada launched in February 1994 a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to develop guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Richter Krever was still reluctant to submit his report, at that time several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for the management of blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of the people had confidence in the blood-conservation system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through work in this area during the following years, we have regained public confidence," she says, before proudly stressing that by the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting in accordance with the precautionary principle.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
`And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we are referring to one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, which says that exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is manifested by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999 no blood was taken from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proven that this disease is being transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied certainly has a meaning.
In 1999, a much more precise technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which enable the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than one week.
Thus, the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transferring AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
`In other words, it means that 12 million blood canisters would have to be distributed before someone was infected with HIV.
As Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preserves every year, it would take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmission through a blood preserve.
I think you can feel comfortable with this today when you get or write a blood transfusion to restore your health', says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogens can get into the system.
Only last year did the Chikungunya virus appear on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted through insects over the blood.
We need to continuously monitor', Dr. Décary continues, before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient supply in addition to a safe supply.
`The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, of which, on average, only 3% of the population of Quebec is suitable for blood donation.
Every healthy person, who is 18 years of age or older and who meets the eligibility criteria, can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have been ill with AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
`With this 3% we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep it and make it become regular donors.
Life is so hectic today that you rarely find the time to spend an hour in blood donation', Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec not only supplies blood preserves, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eye drops and skin, which are almost exclusively used in severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which is also managed by the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, contains blood from stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases such as leukaemia.
`A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand annually.
`We should probably start to make it available for transplants early next year', Dr. Décary explains, which describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
`Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
