The Psychology of Surrendering - or why we are willing to pay more
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play Lotto, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the volunteers were examined by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, however, an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cortex, was measured in the event of loss of the auction, where the overshooting of the opponent plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore felt that the price increase could be explained by avoiding overreaction of the strike.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should participate against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their efforts.
Another group was also promised $15 reward, in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was merely that the emphasis was on winning, while the emphasis was on losing.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "opposite losing" group were prepared for higher stakes than those in the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from previous economic theory.
In fact, these have only justified the practices observed at auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should your doctor visit you?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from one another.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different species: in hepatitis A and E, by the digestive tract (for example by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vagina secretory or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B at any rate, against virus C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, and break-in irritation.
After that, the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine darkens, and recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Around 1 million people worldwide die from the much more severe diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected patients are in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen secretly destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more common: those who have undergone blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooers.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor for the first signs of unknown origin.
In due course, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, thus preventing the risk of infection and preventing cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 for the first time of patient representation worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, its emergence and the importance of early detection.
