Intelligent car imitates the flight of the hummel
What would be the best method for developing new technologies to prevent accidents, if not to imitate barrier sensors from the nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project inspired the Nissan engineers of Hummeln to create new systems to prevent accidents was presented.
In cooperation with the Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C type B biomimetic system controlled by autoboters, a mini-car, equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers seized the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180 degree field of vision within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in parts of seconds, and the autobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Contrary to previous systems, this manoeuvre takes place purely instinctively.
"If not, the autobot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Autobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The entire process must reflect the behaviour of bees when they avoid other bees.
And this has to be done in a fraction of a second.
However, avoiding, unlike the bees, can not be up, down, or even diagonal - it can be only two-dimensional, only in the direction of turning the tyres.
While the bees here are open to endless possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotational movement, respectively acceleration and braking, at the autobot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy-efficient, and therefore have a longer lifetime than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process some inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous manoeuvres, so it constantly uses only a handful of KB memory.
No gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories are required.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan, will be in production as a series within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
