The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already appeared a few days ago, when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the 700 billion dollar savings package of the White House: a large part of the Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This confirms yesterday's issue of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis in progress is spreading the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided into its old and moderate East Coast souls, who always favored the state institutions and the business community, and those neo-conservative who are hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, and who are, above all, winning voters in the south and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its ascent to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example just mentioned is, however, only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even already represents: not only in the United States, also in the entire West and perhaps beyond these will be affected by them.
In both the countries and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-awaited events which are finally taking shape under these new conditions and which come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unheard-of renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries, and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of households living in a single state.
This is a direct political problem for governments: how to behave towards the families concerned, which are indeed a huge mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears to be global in economic terms, and politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have gone out of the way and lost its right to speak: the EU has given the clear proof of this, which, because of its division into different national and international conflicts, cannot find a common way.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, above all, distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more serious, only the United States is in the economic situation to save itself without any foreign aid.
In addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: therefore, two conditions – under certain circumstances – that are not to be over-emphasized, in which otherwise no international organization and no market will be able to take advantage of in a similar way.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed on the national-state element is in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that has recently been attached to a closely related sector in the economy: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now that we have been so convinced that we have long since entered a networked global empire, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of immaterial, that we must at once determine how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
While these can certainly all be transported from one place to another in the world, they are still connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, one who has such a territory, compared to another who lives in an unharvested, waterless or oil-free territory, is in favor.
I now come to the second novelty, which requires a brief boost.
Anyone who says territory, government, politics also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is knowledge about the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to deal with things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of deterrence over the existing guides, especially those of the economy, which have emerged as inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a certain sense, still worrying aspect: a loss of confidence, inadvertentness, an image of inadequacies, a sense of distance, which is all directed towards a whole class of managers of the Western countries.
It seems to be the conviction among large sections of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their Way of Life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose status the majority represents as always more alien and permissive.
The demand for leadership thus feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of the demise of the leading class and of the conventional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the unwarranted reversal of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, over the collapse of the Labour Party in the UK, towards the rebellion of the American MPs against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value regarding what is happening today in the lower social strata of the West and is further reinforced by the financial crisis and driven up to overdimensionality.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
