Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of excluding cinemas, which began with the birth of the great multi-salt complexes in the periphery, means in the long term death for the uni-salt cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the features of a cultural crime.
These are mostly historical places full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom one has covered a piece of street full of emotions", says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It's the story of a suburbs cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these ticks paid for the most part the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main perpetrators are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years Lombardy leads the lists, 81 it is in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "although it is useful that new structures also arise, but first and foremost is the preservation of the already existing one, because closes a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the missing state for the fund of the trade association remains outside eight: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to obtain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros would be needed in the year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, because of the fears of the old cinemas, has decided to protect them by an agreement between the community and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy, which aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Tax concessions for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport are also included under the above measures: driving into the traffic-limited areas of the centre and parking more cheap parking fees.
"It's a happy initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
Certainly, however, we also need a better audio and video equipment to be able to align against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because in the end, the audience is more demanding today.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that led me to establish the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had played with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
