When the energy emerges from the waves, suddenly the Great Ones rise.
It is a non-diverse source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and only now does this seem to understand the world's great energy companies.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and also seeking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; not by chance these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
As the price of oil fell by 1980, the idea of marine energy is being ignored, but environmental organizations and the increase in the price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be met by the energies generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to the doubling of the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
The currents and tides would also be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract in 2005 to set up a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies in the traditional energy sector that rely on marine energy production.
"Chevron is investigating these technologies" – the spokesman of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal – and is considering the possibility of working with us."
It is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being promoted by the United States in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers are talking about an increasing interest.
Still improved technologies.
Experts speak of a technology that is still emerging, not least since the last doubts from environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of rather small size and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with much greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are different possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of connected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is transformed into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind which are only awaiting state approval. Part of the energy generated could also be used for military installations.
Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parking space using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movement during the tides drives the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of possible clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Production Research, a particular interest deserves the potential that exists in times.
Although this is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
In particular, tidal energy is what has led federal states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest already 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million in 2009 are already planned.
